        <title type="html"><![CDATA[Letters]]></title>
        <id>https://igorcasmarques.github.io/micro-blog/letters</id>
        <link href="https://igorcasmarques.github.io/micro-blog/letters"/>
        <updated>2024-04-17T00:00:00.000Z</updated>
        <summary type="html"><![CDATA[I still love them, even though they are largely obsolete.]]></summary>
        <content type="html"><![CDATA[<p>As long as they don't ask me to do anything, I love when friends write to me. It's a special thing to exchange text-mediated, long-form accounts of our lives. It rarely happens anymore, what with instant messaging and video calls; it's just not practical.</p>
<p>But there was a time in my life when handwritten letters were my main form of communication. In 2007-2009, when I was a missionary for <a href="https://www.churchofjesuschrist.org/" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">The Church of Jesus Christ of Latter-day Saints</a>, I could only communicate with people outside of the area I lived in by mail (with very few exceptions).</p>
<p>Here's a stash of letters that I received during that time:</p>
<img src="https://media.licdn.com/dms/image/D4E22AQH_PK_Ks2K_Mg/feedshare-shrink_800/0/1713372461083?e=1717027200&amp;v=beta&amp;t=J7A0YcU9oFOuDy00kCT4SZ4mF6oCIL85VtC8DHSCjoI" alt="Picture of a pile of letters.'" width="500" height="auto">
<p>I can't describe the joy I felt when I found one of these waiting for me in my mailbox. In fact, these letters were so special to me that I eventually married their sender.</p>]]></content>
